-- India's Sensex Advances, Approaching Record as Coal India Surges on Debut
-- B y   R a j h k u m a r   K   S h a a w
-- 2010-11-04T05:06:20Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-04/sensex-approaches-record-amid-foreign-inflows-as-coal-india-jumps-on-debut.html
India’s stocks rose, with the
benchmark index near a record, as surging foreign inflows helped
to absorb the nation’s largest initial share sale and the U.S.
central bank expanded support for the world’s biggest economy.  Coal India Ltd., the world’s No. 1 producer of the fuel,
surged 34 percent after selling 152 billion rupees ($3.4
billion) of shares at the top of the marketed price range.  Tata
Consultancy Services Ltd.  and  Infosys Technologies Ltd. , the two
biggest software services exporters, gained at least 1.4 percent
after the Federal Reserve said yesterday it will buy an
additional $600 billion of Treasuries through June to bolster
economic growth.  “Investors are cheering the Coal India IPO,” said  Alex Mathews , head of research at Geojit BNP Paribas Financial
Services Ltd. in Kochi. “Those who missed out on the IPO will
get a chance to buy it now. Foreign inflows into our country
will rise for the growth if offers.”  The Bombay Stock Exchange’s Sensitive Index, or  Sensex ,
gained 343.57, or 1.7 percent, to 20,809.31 at 10:35 a.m. in
Mumbai. The S&P CNX  Nifty  Index on the National Stock Exchange
rose 1.4 percent to 6,247. The  BSE 200 Index  increased 1.2
percent to 2,633.53.  The gauge has gained 29 percent from the May 25 low,
approaching the record closing high of 20,873.33 on Jan. 8,
2008, and is the best performer this year among the world’s 10
biggest stock markets.  Overseas  investors  bought a net  9.3 billion rupees  ($209
million) of Indian equities on Nov. 2, extending this year’s
record inflows to 1.2 trillion rupees, according to data on the
 website  of the Securities and Exchange Board of India.  Coal India  Coal India soared 34 percent to 327.7 rupees. Investors
pulled money from banks to buy the Kolkata-based company’s
shares, causing rates for three-month  corporate debt  to almost
double. Coal India attracted bids worth at least $48.7 billion,
exceeding the gross domestic product of neighboring Sri Lanka,
as energy demand in an accelerating economy and a surging stock
market helped draw record inflows.  Coal India was initiated at “outperform” by Credit Suisse
Group AG, which cited the country’s chronic coal shortages and
the company’s “superior” earnings. The brokerage set its
share-price target at 350 rupees, according to a report by
Mumbai-based  Neelkanth Mishra  and  Riya Bhattacharya .  Infosys climbed 1.4 percent to 3,067 rupees, while Tata
Consultancy increased 1.6 percent to 1,069.8 rupees. The U.S.
accounts for at least a third of India’s software exports.  Hindalco Industries Ltd. , the aluminum producer that
controls U.S.-based Novelis Inc., added 2.3 to 223.85 rupees.
 Sterlite Industries (India) Ltd. , the biggest copper and zinc
producer, increased 1.6 percent to 179.3 rupees. Three-month-
delivery copper rose as much as 1.3 percent on the London Metal
Exchange. Aluminum in London rose 0.9 percent.  Sobha Developers Ltd.  gained 2.7 percent to 370.9 rupees
after it was initiated at “buy” at BNP Paribas, which said the
company has a “strong growth trajectory.” The brokerage has a
share-price estimate of 409 rupees, according to a report by
 Sandeep Mathew .  To contact the reporter on this story:
